Quarto vs Rmarkdown vs Markdown

  • Markdown is a lightweight markup language with plain text formatting syntax. This has nothing to do with R, it is about formatting only.
  • Rmarkdown is a variant of Markdown that allows to include R code that is executed and the results are included in the document.
  • Quarto is a new document format that is based on Rmarkdown (and backwards compatible) but has more features, looks nicer and is more flexible. Quarto works with other languages as well, not only R.

Descriptive statistics

tapply(x, groups, func) applies a function func to some data x grouped by groups.

library(tidyverse)
labwide <- read_csv("Datasets/labresults_wide_full.csv")[, -1 ]
mean(labwide$NEUT)
## [1] 20.40164
sd(labwide$NEUT)
## [1] 11.29079

Descriptive statistics

tapply(x, groups, func) applies a function func to some data x grouped by groups.

tapply(labwide$NEUT, labwide$ARM, mean)
## AGRIPPAL    FLUAD  PLACEBO 
## 21.30952 23.20000 16.65000
tapply(labwide$NEUT, labwide$Timepoint, mean)
##       D0       D1 
## 17.67213 23.13115
tapply(labwide$NEUT,
  paste(labwide$ARM, labwide$Timepoint, sep="."), mean)
## AGRIPPAL.D0 AGRIPPAL.D1    FLUAD.D0    FLUAD.D1  PLACEBO.D0  PLACEBO.D1 
##    19.71429    22.90476    17.85000    28.55000    15.35000    17.95000

Simple t.test

We define logical vectors to help us select the desired data.

fluad    <- labwide$ARM == "FLUAD"
agrippal <- labwide$ARM == "AGRIPPAL"

d0 <- labwide$Timepoint == "D0"
d1 <- labwide$Timepoint == "D1"

Simple t.test

Paired or not paired?

x <- labwide$NEUT
t.test(x[d0 & fluad], x[d1 & fluad])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x[d0 & fluad] and x[d1 & fluad]
## t = -3.1591, df = 37.48, p-value = 0.003125
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -17.559929  -3.840071
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     17.85     28.55

Simple t.test

Paired or not paired?

t.test(x[d0 & fluad], x[d1 & fluad], paired=TRUE)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  x[d0 & fluad] and x[d1 & fluad]
## t = -6.26, df = 19, p-value = 5.193e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true mean difference is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -14.277528  -7.122472
## sample estimates:
## mean difference 
##           -10.7

Simple t.test

The object returned by t.test is a list with the results of the test.

res <- t.test(x[d0 & fluad], x[d1 & fluad], paired=TRUE)
res$p.value
## [1] 5.192807e-06

We can directly insert the p-value into a text using backticks: `r format.pval(res$p.value)`.

Result:

We can directly insert the p-value into a text using backticks: 5.1928e-06.

Broom: cleaning up data

tidy() cleans up messy results of various standard statistical tests and formats them into a nice, clean, TIDY data frame (or, rather, a tibble).

library(broom)
tidy(t.test(x[d0 & fluad], x[d1 & fluad], paired=TRUE))

Caveat: paired data

We must make sure that all the data points are paired!

Summary - Let’s bring all concepts together

General advice

  • Force yourself to use R/Rmarkdown for everything. It will pay off.
  • If it is stupid but it works, it is not stupid.
  • Work with real data rather than examples. If you know what you want to do, the learning will be more effective.
  • However, when trying a new package or function, first try it on the examples included, then try to use it on your data.
  • Always create a project directory
  • use sessionInfo() to document the environment
